::"The And Stance" Technique::In the Three Conversations Model, what is the purpose of "The And Stance" technique in the "What Happened?" conversation?{
~To agree with the other person's version of events to avoid conflict #The And Stance doesn't mean agreeing with their version or abandoning your own—it means holding space for both perspectives as potentially valid simultaneously. You're not conceding; you're recognizing complexity.
=To acknowledge that both perspectives can be simultaneously valid rather than fighting about who's right #"The And Stance" means recognizing that both perspectives can be valid at the same time\: "You see it this way AND I see it this way." This moves you from debate (who's right?) to learning (what can we both understand?). The common mistake in the "What Happened" conversation is assuming certainty about facts.
~To add more evidence and facts to prove your interpretation is correct #The And Stance isn't about gathering more evidence to win the argument—it's about accepting that facts are often disputed and both interpretations might have merit.
~To delay making a decision until more information is available #The And Stance isn't a delay tactic—it's a reframing technique that allows you to proceed with the conversation while acknowledging multiple valid perspectives.
}

